description: A licensed British reprint of EC's Haunt of Fear. Only a single issue was published, but it came to the attention of George H. Pumphrey, a British counterpart to and advocate of Frederic Wertham, and publisher of Comics and Your Children, Viciousness in Comics - A Recent Example, and later What Children Think of Their Comics. Pumphrey attacked this specific comic in his column in the Times Educational Supplement on 17th September 1954, kicking off a storm of controversy against American horror titles in the U.K., and leading the British government's Ministry for Education to request Pumphrey's own copy of Haunt of Fear #1 for study by a special committee, which in turn led to the passage of a new law a year later, still in force to this day, prohibiting the sale or publication of books, magazine or comics carrying comic strips where the stories depicted crimes, acts of violence or horrific incidents in such a way that it would "tend to corrupt" a child who might fall into the hands of young children.
name: Haunt of Fear
